rolled people count equals the enrollment number.\n\nI think there might be a mismatch here. Let me check what fields the real code would produce in the reporting sub-key vs what the mock expects.\n\nReal code reporting sub-key fields for ttc_application:\nFrom the load function (KEYRESET + load):\n- reporting_status ✓\n- evaluations_reporting_status ✓\n- prereq_no_count ✓\n- evaluations ✓\n- eval_teaching_readiness ✓\n- eval_teaching_readiness_not_ready_now_count ✓\n- evaluator_ratings_below_3 ✓\n- evaluations_submitted_count ✓\n- latest_evaluation_datetime_est ✓\n\nAnd array counts: if any field starting with `i_` is an array, it becomes `{fieldname}_count`. This would give things like:\n- If `i_course_wishlist_yp` is an array → `course_wishlist_yp_count`\n- If `i_special_interest_groups` is an array → `special_interest_groups_count`\n- etc.\n\nBut the mock expects:\n- enrolled_people_count: 45\n- org_courses_count: 8\n- prettc_date_to_deadline_days: 30\n\n`org_courses_count` would come from `i_org_courses` being an array. But `i_org_courses` is NOT in REPORTING_FIELDS, so it wouldn't be kept in the data, but the count IS computed for all arrays before filtering. So if `i_org_courses` were an array in the original data, `org_courses_count` would be set.\n\nBut in the real form data, `i_org_courses` is likely a repeater field (array of objects). So yes, `org_courses_count` would be computed.\n\n`prettc_date_to_deadline_days: 30` — this is NOT a count. There's no logic in the TypeScript code that computes `prettc_date_to_deadline_days`. This is probably calculated in the legacy Python code but NOT ported to the TypeScript code.\n\nSo we have at least one mismatch:\n1. `enrolled_people_count` — The mock expects this to be 45 (equal to `i_enrollment`), but the real code doesn't produce this field from `i_enrollment` (it's a number, not an array).\n2. `prettc_date_to_deadline_days` — The mock expects this but the real code doesn't compute it.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the mock more carefully. Maybe `enrolled_people_count` IS the count of items in `i_enrolled_people` array. In the real form data, `i_enrolled_people` would be a repeater field with multiple entries. If the user enrolled 45 people, it would be an array of 45 objects. So `enrolled_people_count` would be 45 (array length). That makes sense!\n\nAnd `org_courses_count: 8` would be the length of the `i_org_courses` array.\n\nSo these WOULD be produced correctly by the array-counting logic, as long as `i_enrolled_people` and `i_org_courses` are arrays in the original form data. They wouldn't be in REPORTING_FIELDS so they wouldn't be in the output `data`, but their counts WOULD be computed.\n\nOK, so that looks correct.\n\nNow, `prettc_date_to_deadline_days: 30` — this is not a count. It seems to be the number of days between the pre-TTC date and some deadline. This would need specific logic to compute, and I don't see it in the TypeScript code.\n\nHmm, but this is in the MOCK_REPORTS_DATA (by_user view), not the MOCK_SUMMARY_DATA (by_form_type view). The mock is supposed to be the canonical shape. If the real code doesn't produce `prettc_date_to_deadline_days`, then the admin JS won't find it, but the admin JS might not use it either...\n\nActually, the task says: \"If a field in the mock is a number, the real output must produce a number, not a string.\" And \"Top-level keys match (same field names in real vs mock).\"\n\nSo if the mock has `prettc_date_to_deadline_days` but the real code doesn't produce it, that's a shape mismatch that could break admin JS that tries to read it.\n\nBut wait — let me check what the admin page JS actually uses. The mock is supposed to be the canonical shape spec, but maybe the admin JS doesn't actually read `prettc_date_to_deadline_days`.\n\nActually, I should focus on what the task asks: check if Task 6 is fully implemented. Task 6 says to compare shapes and fix mismatches. The commit `f3cd732` was already applied to fix the `by_form_type` view. Let me check if there are remaining mismatches.\n\nLet me also check the get-by-user route and get-by-form-type route to see how data is served.\n\nActually, let me re-read the routes to see if they do any transformation.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"42310003-5b42-4a27-b087-b2860cdc53e2","uuid":"60d0d7c0-1ff9-47af-901b-1626e7fde953"}
