se_matches: {},\n    },\n    instance: {\n      data: { i_fname, i_lname, i_enrolled_people, i_org_courses },  // filtered by reportingFields\n      form_instance: \"...\",\n      app_status: \"...\",\n      eval_status: \"...\",\n      ttc_metadata: {...},\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\nWait, the integrity code doesn't set `last_update_datetime_est`. Let me check...\n\nIn the integrity code (user-integrity.ts), for each form instance:\n```\nfd.form_instance = fiRaw;\nfd.app_status = appStatus;\nfd.eval_status = evalStatus;\n```\n\nThere's no `last_update_datetime_est` computation. The mock has `last_update_datetime_est: \"03/28/2026 14:30\"` but the real code doesn't set this field. That's a MISMATCH!\n\nActually wait, let me re-check. The form data from GCS might already have `last_update_datetime_est` if it was set during the upload process. Let me check...\n\nIn the integrity code, `fd` starts as `{ ...ud.form_data[ft][fiRaw] }`, which would include any fields already present on the form instance, including `last_update_datetime_est` if it was set. But `last_update_datetime_est` is computed by the user-summary load function (not the integrity load). Looking at the summary code, `last_update_datetime_est` is computed from `last_update_datetime` via `utcToEastern()`. The integrity code doesn't do this conversion.\n\nBut wait — the form data in GCS might have `last_update_datetime_est` as a stored field from when the form was submitted. If the upload endpoint sets it, then it would be present. Let me check if the form data already has `last_update_datetime_est`...\n\nActually, looking at the integrity mock more carefully:\n```\ndefault: {\n  data: {\n    i_fname: \"Maria\",\n    i_lname: \"Garcia\",\n    i_enrolled_people: { p1: \"John\", p2: \"Sarah\", p3: \"Mike\" },\n    i_org_courses: { c1: \"HP Barcelona\", c2: \"YES Paris\" },\n  },\n  last_update_datetime_est: \"03/28/2026 14:30\",\n  form_instance: \"app-001\",\n}\n```\n\n`last_update_datetime_est` is a top-level