{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_2026040622534168dd4c666a664e88","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"glm-5.1","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Excellent findings! Now I have a clear picture of the data shape compatibility:\n\n### Key findings:\n\n1. **`prettc_date_to_deadline_days`**: This is **computed client-side** in the reports page JS (render.ts lines 197-208), NOT read from the API response. So the mock having this field is misleading — it's set by the client JS. The real data doesn't need to include it. ✓ No issue.\n\n2. **`enrolled_people_count` and `org_courses_count` in reports page**: These ARE read from the API as `_application[rk]['enrolled_people_count']` and `_application[rk]['org_courses_count']`. The real code computes these from array fields. BUT — looking at the mock, these are inside the `reporting` sub-key of the per-instance data. In the real by_user output, the reporting key DOES contain these counts (they're computed in the load function from array data fields). So the real code WOULD produce them as long as `i_enrolled_people` and `i_org_courses` are arrays in the form data. ✓ Should be correct.\n\nWait, actually... `enrolled_people_count` in the mock reports data is inside the `reporting` sub-key:\n```\nreporting: {\n  reporting_status: \"complete\",\n  enrolled_people_count: 45,\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd the client JS accesses `_application[rk]['enrolled_people_count']`. So `rk` is `'reporting'`? Let me re-check...\n\nActually, in the reports page, `rk` is defined as the reporting key. Let me check... Looking at the explore results: `_application[rk]['enrolled_people_count']` where `rk` is likely `'reporting'`. In the real by_user data, the reporting sub-key IS the KEY ('reporting'), so `_application['reporting']['enrolled_people_count']` would work if the count is in the reporting sub-key. And it IS — the load function puts counts into `fd[KEY][strRemovePrefix(q, 'i_') + '_count']` which is `fd['reporting']['enrolled_people_count']`. ✓\n\n3. **`last_update_datetime_est` in integrity**: The integrity page JS reads `_application['last_update_datetime_est']`. The integrity load code doesn't compute this — it doesn't convert `last_update_datetime` to `last_update_datetime_est` like the summary code does. However, the stored form data might already have `last_update_datetime_est` as a field... Let me think about this.\n\nIn the integrity code:\n```javascript\nconst fd: any = { ...ud.form_data[ft][fiRaw] };\nfd.form_instance = fiRaw;\n```\n\nSo `fd` starts as a copy of the raw form data. If the raw form data has `last_update_datetime_est`, it would be preserved. But if it only has `last_update_datetime`, then the integrity output won't have `last_update_datetime_est`.\n\nThe summary code explicitly converts:\n```javascript\nif (fd['last_update_datetime']) {\n  fd['last_update_datetime_est'] = utcToEastern(fd['last_update_datetime'] as string);\n}\n```\n\nBut the integrity code doesn't do this. This means:\n- If the form data has `last_update_datetime` but not `last_update_datetime_est`, the integrity output won't have `last_update_datetime_est`\n- The integrity page JS tries to read `_application['last_update_datetime_est']` which would be undefined\n\nThis is a **BUG**! The integrity load should convert `last_update_datetime` to `last_update_datetime_est` just like the summary code does.\n\n4. **Settings data shape**: `getAdminConfig()` returns `config.raw_config` which is `{ i_whitelisted_user: [{...}] }`. This matches MOCK_SETTINGS_DATA. ✓\n\n5. **`evaluations` in by_user for reports page**: The reports page JS accesses `_application[rk]['evaluations']` where `rk = 'reporting'`. In the by_user data, the reporting sub-key has `evaluations` as a reference map `{ evaluatorEmail: { ve: name } }`. The reports page JS then resolves these references by looking up full evaluation objects from `user_data`. So the by_user data having references (not full instances) is correct — the reports page JS resolves them itself. ✓\n\nWait, but the mock shows `evaluations: {}` in the reporting sub-key of the reports data, not an array. That's the reference map. The reports page JS iterates this to build the evaluation list. So the shape is correct. ✓\n\n6. **Data types in integrity**: The mock shows `i_enrolled_people` as `{ p1: \"John\", p2: \"Sarah\" }` (an object), and the integrity page JS uses `Object.keys(_application['data']['i_enrolled_people']).length`. But in the real data, `i_enrolled_people` would be an array (repeater field), not an object. So `Object.keys([...]).length` would still work (gives array length), but the shape is different.\n\nActually, looking at the integrity code's field filtering:\n```javascript\nconst reportingFields = {\n  'i_enrolled_people': '',\n  ...\n};\n```\n\nWith `fieldSpec = ''`, the code just passes `i_enrolled_people` through as-is. If the form data has it as an array, the output would have it as an array. The client JS `Object.keys(array).length` would still give the correct count. ✓\n\nSo the main bug I've found is:\n\n**BUG: `last_update_datetime_est` not computed in integrity load.** The integrity load function (`user-integrity.ts`) doesn't convert `last_update_datetime` to `last_update_datetime_est` like the summary load does. The integrity page JS reads `_application['last_update_datetime_est']`, which would be undefined.\n\nLet me also double-check the data shape for the integrity page more carefully. The mock shows:\n```\n{\n  email: {\n    ttc_application: {\n      default: {\n        data: { i_fname, i_lname, i_enrolled_people, i_org_courses },\n        last_update_datetime_est: \"...\",\n        form_instance: \"...\",\n      },\n      integrity: {\n        enrolled_matches: {},\n        org_course_matches: {},\n      },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\nThe real integrity code produces:\n```\n{\n  email: {\n    ttc_application: {\n      integrity: {\n        enrolled_matches: {},\n        org_course_matches: {},\n      },\n      fi: {  // form instance key (not 'default')\n        fiEmail: { ...form data... }  // or just form data if no fiEmail\n      },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\nWait, the mock uses `default` as the instance key. In the real code, form instances skip `default`:\n```javascript\nfor (const fiRaw of Object.keys(ud.form_data[ft])) {\n  if (fiRaw === 'default') continue;  // SKIP default!\n```\n\nHmm, so the integrity code skips `default` instances! But the mock uses `default` as the key. Is this a bug?\n\nLooking at the mock:\n```javascript\n\"maria.garcia@example.com\": {\n  ttc_application: {\n    default: { ... },\n    integrity: { ... },\n  },\n}\n```\n\nBut the real code would produce something like:\n```javascript\n\"maria.garcia@example.com\": {\n  ttc_application: {\n    integrity: { ... },\n    \"some-instance-key\": { ... },\n  },\n}\n```\n\nBecause the form data instance keys are like `ttc-country-dates-email` or similar, not `default`.\n\nWait, but `default` is a special key in the form data that stores the initial page data. The form instance keys are the actual submissions. The mock uses `default` as the instance key for simplicity. In reality, the instance key would be something like `default-email@domain.com` or a specific TTC identifier.\n\nBut looking at the fiEmail parsing:\n```javascript\nif (fiRaw.includes('-')) {\n  const fiArr = fiRaw.split('-');\n  if (fiArr.length >= 2 && !fiArr[1].includes('@')) {\n    fiEmail = fiArr[0];\n    fi = fiArr[1];\n  } else {\n    fi = fiArr[0];\n    fiEmail = fiArr[1] || null;\n  }\n} else {\n  fi = fiRaw;\n}\n```\n\nIf `fiRaw` is `default-email@domain.com`:\n- fiArr = ['default', 'email@domain.com']\n- fiArr[1] includes '@'\n- fi = fiArr[0] = 'default'\n- fiEmail = fiArr[1] = 'email@domain.com'\n\nThen `ftData['default']` gets created, and the email is stored inside: `ftData['default']['email@domain.com'] = fd`.\n\nBut the mock has `ftData['default'] = fd` directly (no email nesting).\n\nActually, looking at the integrity code again:\n```javascript\nif (fiEmail) {\n  userDataByEmail[ue][ft][fi][fiEmail] = fd;\n} else {\n  userDataByEmail[ue][ft][fi] = fd;\n}\n```\n\nIf there's a fiEmail, the data is nested: `[fi][fiEmail] = fd`. The mock doesn't show this nesting — it shows `[fi] = fd` directly.\n\nBut wait, the mock has `default` as the key, and the form data key for TTC applications is typically something like `default-email@domain.com`. So `fiRaw` = `default-email@domain.com` → `fi` = `default`, `fiEmail` = `email@domain.com`. The real output would be:\n```\nttc_application: {\n  default: {\n    \"email@domain.com\": { data, form_instance, ... }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nBut the mock shows:\n```\nttc_application: {\n  default: {\n    data: {...},\n    last_update_datetime_est: \"...\",\n    form_instance: \"...\",\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThese are different shapes! The real code has an extra nesting level with the email.\n\nNow, how does the integrity page JS consume this? Let me check...\n\nFrom the explore results: \"The JS iterates `user_data[email]['ttc_application'][selected_ttc]`.\" And \"enrolled_matches at lines 71-77, 96, 175-176: `_applicant[key]['enrolled_matches']`\".\n\nWait, `_applicant[key]` — what is `key`? In the integrity page JS, the iteration would be over keys of `user_data[email]['ttc_application'][selected_ttc]`. If `selected_ttc` is something like `default`, then the keys would be `email@domain.com` (the fiEmail) and `integrity`. The JS would iterate these keys and look for `enrolled_matches` inside each.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The mock data structure is what the Python legacy code produces. The mock is the canonical shape. The TypeScript code should produce the same shape. If it doesn't, the admin JS won't work correctly.\n\nLooking at the Python integrity code (which I haven't read), it would produce:\n```\nemail: {\n  ttc_application: {\n    instance: {\n      data: {...},\n      ...\n    },\n    integrity: {\n      enrolled_matches: {...},\n      ...\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\nWhere `instance` could have fiEmail nesting or not. Let me look at what the integrity page render.ts actually expects.\n\nActually, from the explore results for the integrity page:\n- Line 71-77: `_applicant[key]['enrolled_matches']` — iterates keys looking for enrolled_matches\n- Line 88: `if (enrolled_matches_count > 0 || org_course_matches_count > 0)` — checks if there are matches\n- Line 89: `Object.keys(_application['data']['i_enrolled_people']).length` — reads from data\n\nWhere `_applicant` is `user_data[email]['ttc_application'][selected_ttc]` and `key` iterates over its children. So the JS looks at each child of `ttc_application[selected_ttc]` and checks if it has `enrolled_matches`.\n\nIf the real data has fiEmail nesting:\n```\nttc_application: {\n  default: {\n    \"email@domain.com\": { data: {...}, form_instance: \"...\" }\n  },\n  integrity: {\n    enrolled_matches: {...},\n    org_course_matches: {},\n  },\n}\n```\n\nThen iterating keys of `ttc_application['default']` would give `[\"email@domain.com\"]`. The JS would check `_applicant[\"email@domain.com\"]['enrolled_matches']` which would be undefined (it's not there). Then it would also need to check `ttc_application['integrity']['enrolled_matches']`.\n\nHmm, but `integrity` is NOT a child of `default`. It's a sibling of `default` under `ttc_application`. So the JS would iterate keys of `ttc_application` (the form type), not `ttc_application['default']`.\n\nWait, I think I was confused. Let me re-read the explore results:\n\"The JS iterates `user_data[email]['ttc_application'][selected_ttc]`.\"\n\nSo `selected_ttc` is the TTC instance key (like `default`). The JS gets `user_data[email]['ttc_application']['default']` and iterates its keys.\n\nIn the mock data:\n```\nttc_application: {\n  default: {\n    data: {...},\n    last_update_datetime_est: \"...\",\n    form_instance: \"...\",\n  },\n  integrity: {\n    enrolled_matches: {...},\n    ...\n  },\n}\n```\n\nHere, `ttc_application['default']` has keys: `data`, `last_update_datetime_est`, `form_instance`. And `ttc_application['integrity']` has keys: `enrolled_matches`, `org_course_matches`.\n\nBut the JS iterates `user_data[email]['ttc_application'][selected_ttc]` where `selected_ttc = 'default'`. So it's iterating keys of `ttc_application['default']`, which in the mock are `data`, `last_update_datetime_est`, `form_instance`. None of these have `enrolled_matches`.\n\nHmm, that can't be right. Let me look at the actual JS more carefully. Let me re-read the integrity render.ts file.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"42310003-5b42-4a27-b087-b2860cdc53e2","uuid":"3f587aaa-8f20-46c7-a29b-894818a248fc"}
