{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_202604062257312499a6d2e4794f62","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"glm-5.1","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the key data access patterns:\n\n### Reports page (get-by-user endpoint):\n\n1. `_application['${rk}']['enrolled_people_count']` (line 130, 262) — reads from `reporting` sub-key\n2. `_application['${rk}']['org_courses_count']` (line 159, 266) — reads from `reporting` sub-key\n3. `_application['${rk}']['prettc_date_to_deadline_days']` (line 164, 208) — **COMPUTED CLIENT-SIDE** and SET into the reporting sub-key! Line 208: `_application['${rk}']['prettc_date_to_deadline_days'] = _prettc_date_to_deadline_days;`\n4. `_application['${rk}']['evaluations']` (line 218) — reads from `reporting` sub-key, which contains reference maps\n5. `_application['${rk}']['reporting_status']` (line 252)\n6. `_application['last_update_datetime_est']` (line 255) — top-level field\n7. `_application['data']['i_fname']`, etc. (line 194+) — from data sub-key\n8. `_application['form_instance_page_data']['i_ttc_country_and_dates']` (line 195) — from form_instance_page_data\n\nAnd for the `_applicant` (which is `user_data[email]['ttc_application']`):\n9. `_applicant['${rk}']['lifetime_evaluations']` (line 225) — from formType-level reporting\n10. `_applicant['${rk}']['lifetime_eval_teaching_readiness']` (line 246)\n11. `_applicant['${rk}']['lifetime_evaluator_ratings_below_3']` (line 247)\n\nNow, `rk` is the reporting key, which is `'reporting'`. So `_application['reporting']` and `_applicant['reporting']` (at the formType level).\n\nThe real by_user data from `loadUserSummary` produces:\n- `_applicant` = `user_data[email]['ttc_application']` which has:\n  - `reporting`: { lifetime_evaluations, lifetime_eval_teaching_readiness, ... }\n  - `instance_key`: { `data`, `form_instance`, `last_update_datetime_est`, `reporting`: { reporting_status, evaluations, enrolled_people_count, ... } }\n\nBut wait — in the reports page, `_application` = `_applicant[_selected_ttc]`. And `_selected_ttc` comes from the TTC dropdown value, which is like `default`. So `_application` = `user_data[email]['ttc_application']['default']`.\n\nIn the real data, this would be:\n```\nuser_data[email]['ttc_application']['default'] = {\n  fiEmail: {  // if there's fiEmail nesting\n    data: {...},\n    reporting: {...},\n    ...\n  }\n}\n// OR (no fiEmail):\nuser_data[email]['ttc_application']['default'] = {\n  data: {...},\n  reporting: {...},\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nThe JS expects `'data' in _application`, so it expects `data` to be directly on the instance. If there's fiEmail nesting, `data` would be nested under the email key, and the JS would fail.\n\nThis is the same issue I identified for the integrity page. But this is a fundamental issue with how the form instances are stored, not specific to Task 6.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-think this. The summary code does:\n```javascript\nif (fiEmail) {\n  (ftData[fi] as Record<string, unknown>)[fiEmail] = fd;\n} else {\n  ftData[fi] = fd;\n}\n```\n\nSo if there IS a fiEmail (email address extracted from the form instance key), the data is nested. If there isn't, it's flat.\n\nFor TTC applications, the form instance key is like `default-email@domain.com`. This would produce fiEmail nesting.\n\nBut the JS expects NO fiEmail nesting — it expects `_application` (the instance) to have `data` directly.\n\nThis is the same structure that the Python code would have produced. The Python code must have produced the same nesting or flat structure. Since this is a port, the behavior should match.\n\nActually, let me look at the summary page's `invertToByFormType` function. It has special handling for fiEmail nesting:\n```javascript\n// Handle fiEmail nesting: { fiEmail: { ...formData } }\nlet unwrapped = obj;\nif (!('data' in obj) && !('reporting' in obj)) {\n  const keys = Object.keys(obj);\n  if (keys.length === 1 && typeof obj[keys[0]] === 'object' && obj[keys[0]] !== null) {\n    const inner = obj[keys[0]] as Record<string, unknown>;\n    if ('data' in inner || KEY in inner) {\n      unwrapped = inner;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis unwraps the fiEmail nesting for the by_form_type view. But the by_user view (used by the reports page) does NOT unwrap it.\n\nHmm, but the reports page reads `_application['${rk}']` where `rk = 'reporting'`. If `_application` has fiEmail nesting:\n```\n_application = {\n  \"email@domain.com\": {\n    data: {...},\n    reporting: {...},\n    ...\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThen `_application['reporting']` would be undefined, and the JS would fail.\n\nBut the Python code produced the same structure... unless the Python code handled it differently. Since this is a faithful port, the TypeScript code should produce the same output as the Python code. If the Python code had fiEmail nesting in the by_user output, the admin JS would have handled it (or it would have been broken in Python too).\n\nOK, I think I need to step back and focus on what Task 6 specifically asks:\n\n> \"Verify that real GCS data shape matches what the client-side JS expects\"\n> \"If the shape differs, it's likely a bug in the user-summary.ts or user-integrity.ts logic\"\n\nThe key fix already applied (f3cd732) was to flatten the `reporting` key in the by_form_type view. Let me check if there are remaining issues:\n\n1. **Integrity page: `last_update_datetime_est`** — The integrity load doesn't compute this from `last_update_datetime`. The page JS reads `_application['last_update_datetime_est']`. **This is a bug.**\n\n2. **Reports page: fiEmail nesting** — If the real data has fiEmail nesting in the by_user output, the reports page JS won't work. But this depends on the actual form instance keys in the data. The Python code would have the same behavior.\n\n3. **Reports page: `enrolled_people_count` and `org_courses_count`** — These come from array counting in the reporting sub-key. They should be present if the form data has `i_enrolled_people` and `i_org_courses` as arrays. ✓\n\n4. **Reports page: `prettc_date_to_deadline_days`** — Computed client-side, not needed in API response. ✓\n\n5. **Summary page: reporting key flattening** — Fixed in f3cd732. ✓\n\n6. **Settings page: shape** — Matches. ✓\n\nSo the main bug I've found is #1: `last_update_datetime_est` not computed in the integrity load.\n\nLet me fix this.\n\nActually, wait. Let me also check if there are any other issues I might have missed. Let me look at the reporting status field naming more carefully.\n\nThe reports page uses:\n- `_application['${rk}']['eval_teaching_readiness_not_ready_now_count']` (line 147)\n- `_applicant['${rk}']['lifetime_eval_teaching_readiness_not_ready_now_count']` (line 150)\n- `_application['${rk}']['evaluator_ratings_below_3']` (line 153)\n- `_applicant['${rk}']['lifetime_evaluator_ratings_below_3']` (line 155)\n\nBut the real code's KEYRESET uses:\n- `eval_teaching_readiness_not_ready_now_count` ✓\n- `lifetime_eval_teaching_readiness_not_ready_now_count` ✓\n- `evaluator_ratings_below_3` ✓\n- `lifetime_evaluator_ratings_below_3` ✓\n\nThese match. ✓\n\nWait, but line 153: `_application['${rk}']['evaluator_ratings_below_3']` — the real code sets `evaluator_ratings_below_3` in the reporting sub-key (line 232). ✓\n\nAnd line 147: `_application['${rk}']['eval_teaching_readiness_not_ready_now_count']` — the real code sets this (line 231). ✓\n\nOK, let me also check the `_application['data']['i_course_wishlist']` field. In the whitelist: `'i_course_wishlist'` is there. But it's also listed as individual fields: `i_course_wishlist_artexcel`, `i_course_wishlist_hp`, etc. In the real data, `i_course_wishlist` might be an array of selected values (from checkboxes). The whitelist keeps it. ✓\n\nAnd `_application['data']['i_special_interest_groups']` — in the whitelist. ✓\n\nNow, one more thing: the reports page accesses `_application['data']['i_volunteer_mental_fitness']` through evaluations (line 237). But `i_volunteer_mental_fitness` is